		<!-- Begin Comments -->
		
		<b>Comment By Hal Herring, 4-01-09</b>
		<p>Thank the Lord the Coen brothers are taking an interest in rescuing True Grit from John Wayne.  Wayne overwhelmed that old movie, and the Rocky Mountain scenery busted the power of the book, which is set in Oklahoma. I can't wait to see the Coen version.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Bill Croke, 4-01-09</b>
		<p>And yet Smiley, for all her indignation, has made a ton of money and garnered many honors in the New York publishing milieu. So, there's some hypocrisy there. Besides, she lives in Carmel, and despite her Midwestern roots seems to be at home in loony left California. Her politics nauseate me. I have never, nor will, read the woman--not for a thousand acres.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By horst, 4-01-09</b>
		<p>Posted carefully around the hayseed in both instances; but with  rightwingloony libertarian malice in the latter.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Patia, 4-02-09</b>
		<p>You have a point about NY-centric literature, but I think it's balanced somewhat by urban romanticizing of the West.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Tom Page, 4-06-09</b>
		<p>To some extent, it's a function of population and density.  We have exactly one real bookstore in Blaine County, ID and most counties around here have none.  There's a few in Boise, and some scattered here and there in the north and southeast.  Tough to maintain a literary tradition when that's the case, and even harder to have an impact on the bestseller lists.<br />
<br />
As the papers and the bookshops disappear, it becomes even more difficult in the less-peopled west to spread the word about good writing, even with the internet around to make up for it a bit.  I don't think that will have an impact on the quality of western writing though - at least I hope not.</p>
		
		<!-- End Comments -->

